Another key determinant of foundation models’ economic impact is who owns data and models. In

training. However, it likely that the gap between the private models that industry can train and the

messages.content: Does GPT-J work with our pretrained API?
How is the decentralisation, if bittnode runs on a server?

Bittensor consensus runs on distributed validator nodes, implemented with tried-and-trusted Substrate tech. The unique distributed consensus algorithm ensures that the ML nodes (different from validator nodes) are appropriately awarded for contribution of intelligence/useful representations.
I don’t really understand it? So only the reward system is decentralised? Is only the training of the AI decentralised?

The substrate-based blockchain is decentralized over validator nodes the community hosts, the consensus algorithm is decentralized where ML/miner nodes independently communicate assessments to the blockchain validator nodes, and the distributed ML / Mixture-of-Experts / Distillation is decentralized between the ML/miner nodes. So everything is distributed and decentralized, both the reward system and AI training.

trying to understand section 10 of the whitepaper. So here a peer is a mining node correct? It defines dataset, loss and model? in other words, the peer needs to collect data, and has the flexibility to define its own loss function and specify any kind of nn model?

Correct, a peer is a mining node, it defines its dataset, loss and model.
However, the local ML model it defines needs to be suitable for the modality it operates on, e.g. NL or vision.

Also, in practice, it needs to conform to certain representation form factors to allow it to request same-sized representations from remote miners. It then learns weights for a weighted combination of remote representations for a given input (task), and those weights are what determine the remote's usefulness and ultimately its rank when multiplied with the stake of the local miner.
The current template miner has both local and remote-combining Transformer stages, and each is trained to optimize a certain loss, local loss, remote loss, and distillation loss.

So each standard miner wishes to distill the capability of the network's models into its own remote-combining Transformer stage, but it also gets to factor in its own local Transformer stage so if it's superior it still gets overall good performance.
So each miner gets to locally distill a Mixture-of-Experts from the rest of the network.
We believe an approach like this can produce the impressive scaling we need to compete with Google and OpenAI.
https://arxiv.org/abs/2101.03961

embeds.title: Switch Transformers: Scaling to Trillion Parameter Models with...
embeds.description:

Fun Fact about using MLPs:

You can get 16k context windows

for those confused about what this means, allow me to explain.

Humans (maybe other mammals) have an active working memory. Our brains take this and compress it into long term memory. The better your brain is at this task, the more intelligent you are [this can be debated but for sake of brevity bear with me]. 

The largest limiting factor bittensor will face in creating an AGI is not compute or data, but this active working memory length. If some models have short but powerful active working memory, we will get a few really good sentences before it starts to hallucinate. 

GPT-3 is super-human at compression. It takes decades for humans to become 'educated.' It only takes a few weeks at most for self attention to compress. This is amazing!! However, It is not enough, as humans have a much larger active working memory.

If we have a blend of attention and MLPs (remix blocks) sharing information in the network, we may be able to get a global model that has superior compression AND superior active working memory.

Hi Khufu!

Epochs are an AI term, not a crypto mining term. If i give you a dataset with 100 records and a batch size of 5, then your AI model will need 20 iterations to get through the entire data (that's 1 epoch), thats because they represent how many iterations you need to get through the entire dataset. After each epoch, your miner will set weights on the network and contribute what it learned from the dataset to the collective, this is where the mining comes in because this is where you get ranked and subsequently  rewarded if what your model learned is useful to the network.

So in sum, Increasing your batch size will make it so you have less iterations to run thru per epoch, but each iteration will take longer. Your model would also likely learn better with a larger epoch.

so I want to point this out for those who are wondering: Running more miners doesn't mean more tao
having a model that learns novel information will be rewarded proportionally
so if your model has learned the same as others, it won't be rewarded as much

You mean on a single VM? Running multiple VMs would though, correct?

single or multiple won't make much of a difference. rewards are tied to what your model learned. if all your models learned the same thing, your rewards won't be as high as if they had all learned different things that were beneficial to the network as a whole
you're more than welcome to, and you may see an increase in tao rewards initially, but it won't be for long, as more powerful models start entering the network
So how do you create new models?
I'm not understanding, because If I create one model on my machine, and Jane creates a different model on her machine, how is that different from me running two miners on two different machines?

Models are not all identical. Initially in the network everyone will have the same model since everyone will be running the Bittensor `template_miner`. But Jane might have some knowledge of how to build a neural network, so she can bring her own model or build her own model from scratch and join the network. Those models -- due to their different architecture, hyperparameters, etc. -- could be more powerful than the template miner, and hence she might have an advantage
the template miner is just that, a template to get people started on building their own models that can bring their own nuances to the network.
if your model learns how to do a novel skill: e.g. accounting, the network will reward you greatly
if you have 5 models that all learn the same skill, this is not as valuable
